photo.description: Penn Libraries call number: BT131.B67 1762 All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record Warmoldus Kuÿpers Zÿn Boeck Ms. ownership inscription of Warmoldus Kuypers (1732-1797), a Dutch Reformed minister, in brown ink on front pastedown of an edition of Johannes Boskoop's Gods alwetenheid van David (Amsterdam: Nicolaas Byl, 1762; STCN 299364267) . Born in the Netherlands, Kuypers studied at Groningen in 1753 and served in Curaçao until 1768. He then emigrated to America, possibly at the behest of Isaac Rysdyck (d. 1790, a fellow-student at Groningen and pastor in Poughkeepsie, NY) and first ministered at Rhinebeck Flats and Upper Red Hook/Red Hook Landing, NY (1769-1771); subsequently he was called to Hackensack and Schraalenburgh, NJ (1771-1797), where he initially shared responsibility with (and was seen as the less evangelical alternative to) John Henry Goetschius (pastor 1748-1774) and thereafter with Theodorick ("Dirck") Romeyn (pastor 1775-1784) and Solomon Froeligh (pastor 1786-1823). Kuypers took the conferentie side of the conferentie/coetus dispute and had Tory sympathies during the Revolution (though he was briefly taken prisoner by British troops during their raid on Hackensack on 23 March 1780 and held until he was able to convince them of his bona fides; see Leiby 245). He was, however, no partisan: "Trouble I hate," he was remembered as saying (Romeyn 76). References: Corwin, Edward Tanjore. A Manual of the Reformed Church in America (formerly Reformed Protestant Dutch Church), 1628-1902. 4th ed., rev. and enlarged. New York: Board of Publication of the Reformed Church in America, 1902. Drury, John B. The Reformed (Dutch) Church, Rhinebeck, N.Y.: An Historical Address Delivered at the 150th Anniversary of its Organization. Chatham, N.Y.: Courier Steam Printing House, 1881. Gasero, Russell L. Historical Directory of the Reformed Church in America, 1628-2000. Grand Rapids, Mich.: Eerdmans, 2001. Leiby, Adrian C. The Revolutionary War in the Hackensack Valley. Rev. ed. New Brunswick, N.J.: Rutgers University Press, 1992. Romeyn, Theodore B. Historical Discourse Delivered on Occasion of the Re-opening and Dedication of the First Reformed (Dutch) Church, at Hackensack, N.J. New York: Board of Publication of the Reformed Church in America, 1870.

photo.description: Author: Ferdinand I, King of Naples, 1423-1494. Title: Extratto da un libro de razza da cavalli del re Ferrante vechio de Aragona [manuscript]. Origin: [Venice], 1541. This manuscript was possibly first owned by Philippe de Croy, duc d'Arschot, marquis de Renty (after 1533), chevalier de la Toison d'Or, and royal chamberlain. Then, formerly owned by Gharles Gilbert Terray, vicomte de Morel de Vindé, then owned by Jean-Baptiste Huzard. It was sold as part of the Huzard collection in 1843 to Charles Louis Adélaïde Henri Matheron, baron de Curnieu, next sold at auction by Etude Couturier Nicolay at Hôtel Drouot as part of the baron de Curnieu collection, 25 Feb. 1986, lot 144, and then sold at auction at Sotheby's, 5 Dec. 1944, lot 85, to Lawrence J. Schoenberg. Penn Libraries call number: LJS 29 All images from this item Penn in Hand catalog record and facsimile

photo.description: Woodcut device (94 x 69 mm.) of Denys Roce, depicting his arms on a shield, supported by two griffins, hanging from a rose tree with a dog lying at its foot and Roce's monogram "DR" in the background, the whole surrounded by the words ALAVENTVRE TOVT VIENT APONIT QVI PEVT ATENDRE DENIS ROCE (the S in Denis reversed). "[T]hird of Roce's four devices ... The coat of arms may be the legitimate arms of the printer, who had come to France from Scotland. The dogs in the device denote alertness and the scallop shell is the emblem of pilgrims to the shrine of St. James of Campostella [sic]. The rose tree is, of course, a pun on Roce's name."--M. Harman, Printer's and publisher's devices in incunabula in the University of Illinois Library, no. 31. Printed in an incunable edition of St. Augustine's De virtute psalmorum (Paris : Etienne Jehannot for Denis Roce, between 26 June 1500 and 29 May 1501; ISTC ia01352000). Established heading: Roce, Denys, active 1490-1517 Penn Libraries call number: Inc A-1352 All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.description: Henrici Vulpij Vicarij Generalis [Mid-17th-century ms. ownership inscription of Heinrich Fuchs (1624-1689), canon of the Kathedrale St. Nikolaus in Fribourg, Switzerland, and vicar general of the diocese of Lausanne (1658-1663), who inherited a substantial portion of Peter Falck's library. According to this description of another of Falck's books with similar provenance, "After his death Falck's library passed to his daughter Ursula von Praroman. It was subsequently divided between her two sons Nikolaus and Wilhelm, and passed down through their families, to be more or less reunited in the late 17th century in the Capuchin convent at Fribourg. The present volume was one of those inherited by Wilhelm; this group passed by descent to one Anna Marie von Lanthen-Heidt, a wealthy noblewoman who had married Wilhelm's grandson Nikolaus von Praroman en secondes noces. After her husband's death in 1675 Anna gave the books to her friend the vicar-general Heinrich Fuchs. Fuchs in turn gave part of the books to the Capuchins the year before he died; the remainder passed to the convent after his death in 1689." (For more information on Falck's library, see A. Wagner, Peter Falcks Bibliothek und humanistische Bildung (Bern: P. Haupt, 1926).) VIAF entry: Fuchs, Heinrich, 1624-1689] Penn Libraries call number: Inc A-1192 All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.description: Petri Falck & Amicorum Non solum Iherosolimis fuisse Sed Iherolsolimis Bene Vixisse Laudandum est. Peter Falck 1516 [Early ms. ownership inscription of humanist Peter Falck (ca. 1468-1519) and friends in red ink, struck through in brown ink, followed by early ms. inscription quoting a pious saying of St. Jerome in red ink in the same hand between drawings of a Jerusalem cross and an unidentified symbol. Beneath these in dark ink is Falck's dated 16th-century autograph, the name struck through, above a (later?) drawing of his coat of arms. Peter Falck was a Swiss humanist known to Erasmus (cf. his entry in Contemporaries of Erasmus) who made pilgrimages to Jerusalem in 1515 and 1519. He contracted plague during the second pilgrimage and died at Rhodes. The pious inscription in red ink is probably to be associated with his first pilgrimage. Established heading: Falck, Peter, approximately 1468-1519] Penn Libraries call number: Inc A-1192 All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.description: EX LIBRIS STARKENSTEIN [Bookplate of Emil Starkenstein (1884-1942), clinical pharmacology pioneer. A professor at the Univerzita Karlova in Prague, he fled to Holland when the Nazis invaded Czechoslovakia in 1938. In 1941 he was sent to Mauthausen where he perished, though his wife and daughter went into hiding and survived. After the war his scientific papers were donated to Czechoslovakia and are now housed at the Univerzita Karlova. Starkenstein's library was sold before his death to book dealer Ludwig Gottschalk, who hid it from the Nazis and sold it off piecemeal after emigrating to the United States following World War II. Established heading: Starkenstein, Emil, 1884-1942] Penn Libraries call number: Inc V-259 Folio All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record
